"Bizzarri G., Morini G.L.","Greenhouse gas reduction and primary energy savings via adoption of a fuel cell hybrid plant in a hospital",2004,"Applied Thermal Engineering","24","2-3",,"383","400",,,10.1016/j.applthermaleng.2003.09.009,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-0242489299&partnerID=40&md5=9676148307157bfc3e3f1dfeda0a06d0","Department of Architecture, University of Ferrara, Via Quartieri, 8, 44100 Ferrara, Italy; D.I.E.N.C.A., University of Bologna, Viale Risorgimento, 240136 Bologna, Italy","Bizzarri, G., Department of Architecture, University of Ferrara, Via Quartieri, 8, 44100 Ferrara, Italy; Morini, G.L., D.I.E.N.C.A., University of Bologna, Viale Risorgimento, 240136 Bologna, Italy","The Kyoto agreement, expressing great concern about global climate change, has stated emissions of greenhouse gases, especially CO2 from fossil fuel use, need to be reduced. According to this, existing plants have been required to cut emissions; moreover, there has been a greater emphasis on adopting efficient systems in order to reduce the energy losses. Among high efficiency technologies, fuel cells appear to be the most promising for their high efficiency and their very low environmental impact. This paper first reviews the state-of-the-art of fuel cells systems, then simulates the operation of a hybrid fuel cells plant in a ""typical hospital"" analysing how it could optimize the hospitals energetic requirements. Hospitals and sanitary structures are normally characterized by considerable energy demands not often suitable with resolute energy retrofit strategies. Both the considerable primary energy savings and the pollutant emissions reduction, achieved upgrading conventional systems to a fuel cell hybrid plant, have the potential to prompt national boards to support their business development, as long as they achieve a consolidated market penetration. © 2003 Elsevier Ltd. All rights reserved.","Energy requirement; Fuel cells; Greenhouse gases reduction; Primary energy savings","Computer simulation; Energy utilization; Gas emissions; Greenhouse effect; Optimization; Retrofitting; Greenhouse gases; Fuel cells",,,,,,"Libro Bianco per la valorizzazione energetica delle Fonti Rinnovabili (1998) Conferenza Nazionale Energia e Ambiente, , Rome, 25-28 November; Barra, L., Il libro bianco per la valorizzazione energetica delle fonti rinnovabili (2000) La Termotecnica LIV, (1), pp. 27-35; Clini, C., Il protocollo di Kyoto. Un punto di partenza verso la protezione del clima (2002) La Termotecnica LVI, (5); Velonà, F., Dal petrolio al gas naturale. Nuovi assetti e linee di sviluppo nel settore dell'energia (2002) La Termotecnica LVI, (1); Costa, M.H.A., Balestrieri, J.A.P., Comparative study of cogeneration system in a chemical industry (2001) Applied Thermal Engineering, 21 (4), pp. 523-533; Luz-Silvera, J., Beyene, A., Leal, E.M., Santana, J.A., Okada, D., Thermoeconomic analysis of a cogeneration system of a university campus (2002) Applied Thermal Engineering, 22 (13), pp. 1471-1483; Falcitelli, M., Pasini, S., Rossi, N., Tognotti, L., CFD+reactor network analysis: An integrated methodology for the modeling and optimisation of industrial system for energy saving and pollution reduction (2002) Applied Thermal Engineering, 22 (8), pp. 971-979; Gustafsson, S., Optimization and simulation of building energy systems (2000) Applied Thermal Engineering, 20 (18), pp. 1731-1741; Hens, H., Verbeeck, G., Verdonck, B., Impact of energy efficiency measures on the CO2 emissions in the residential sector, a large scale analysis (2001) Energy and Buildings, 33 (3), pp. 275-281; Le Corre, O., Brecq, G., Tazerout, M., Thermoeconomic analysis based on energy structure for combined heat and power (2002) Applied Thermal Engineering, 22 (5), pp. 561-566; Agrafiotis, C., Tsoutsos, T., Energy saving technologies in the European ceramic sector: A systematic review (2001) Applied Thermal Engineering, 21 (12), pp. 1231-1249; Maidment, G.G., Tozer, 